---
1. User Roles & Authentication

There are three roles, each with their own auth:

Patient (User)
- Registers/logs in via /api/user/register and /api/user/login
- Gets a JWT token stored in localStorage
- Every protected request sends Authorization: Bearer <token> in the header
- authUser middleware on the backend decodes the token → extracts userId → injects into req.body

Doctor
- Separate login at /api/doctor/login
- Uses their own JWT token in the Doctor portal
- authDoctor middleware protects doctor routes

Admin
- Hardcoded credentials in .env (ADMIN_EMAIL, ADMIN_PASSWORD)
- On login, backend signs email+password as a JWT string
- authAdmin middleware verifies it matches the stored credentials

---
2. Core Features

Appointment Booking Flow

Patient selects doctor → picks date/time slot
     → POST /api/user/bookAppointment
     → Backend checks if slot already taken (slots_booked map on Doctor model)
     → Creates Appointment document in MongoDB
     → Updates doctor's slots_booked
Doctor model stores booked slots as:
slots_booked: {
  "25_11_2024": ["10:00 am", "11:00 am"],
  "26_11_2024": ["2:00 pm"]
}

Video Consultation

- Uses Firebase Firestore as a WebRTC signaling server
- Patient and doctor both open /video-call
- One side creates an offer → stores in Firestore → other side reads it and sends answer
- Direct peer-to-peer video connection established (no video data goes through Firebase, only the connection handshake)

Doctor Profile Images

- Admin uploads a doctor's photo via the Add Doctor form
- Multer saves the file temporarily to disk
- Backend uploads it to Cloudinary → gets a permanent HTTPS URL
- That URL is stored in the Doctor document in MongoDB

