3. IPFS / Pinata Integration

What problem does it solve?
Medical data is sensitive. Storing it on a central server (MongoDB) means one breach exposes everything. IPFS (InterPlanetary File
System) is a decentralized storage network where data is content-addressed — meaning a file is identified by a hash of its content,
not a location. Pinata is a service that pins files to IPFS so they stay accessible.

How it's used in AUREA:

Patient Profile Image Upload

Patient edits profile → selects new photo
     → Frontend uploads file directly to Pinata API
     → Pinata returns IPFS hash (e.g. "QmXyz...")
     → Frontend constructs URL: https://gateway.pinata.cloud/ipfs/QmXyz...
     → Saves that URL to user profile via PUT /api/user/updateProfileData

Marketplace Data Upload (the main IPFS use case)

Disease conditions in the listing form are restricted to the 7 classes from the
HAM10000 dermatology dataset used to train the AI model:
     Actinic Keratosis, Basal Cell Carcinoma, Benign Keratosis,
     Dermatofibroma, Melanoma, Melanocytic Nevi, Vascular Lesion

Patient fills "List My Data" form on Profile page
     → Optionally selects a skin lesion image (JPG/PNG)
     → If image selected: Frontend uploads image directly to Pinata API
           → Pinata returns imageHash (IPFS hash of the image)
     → Frontend sends form data + imageHash to POST /api/marketplace/list
     → Backend (marketplaceController.js) takes the private fields:
           { disease, ageRange, gender, symptoms, treatmentHistory, medications, imageHash }
     → Converts private fields to JSON → uploads JSON bundle to Pinata via their API
     → Pinata stores on IPFS → returns a content hash (ipfsHash)
     → Backend stores a Marketplace listing in MongoDB:
           { sellerId, disease, ageRange, priceInTON, ipfsHash, imageHash, buyers: [] }
     → Both ipfsHash and imageHash are stored; ipfsHash is NEVER shown to buyers until they pay
     → imageHash is optional — listings without an image are fully supported

Why IPFS for this?
- The data is stored decentrally — not on AUREA's servers
- The patient owns their data (they have the hash)
- Once purchased, a buyer gets a permanent, tamper-proof URL to the dataset
- Nobody can alter the data after upload (content-addressed)

