4. TON Blockchain Integration

What is TON?
TON (The Open Network) is a blockchain developed by Telegram. It's fast and has very low transaction fees (~0.01 TON = fractions of a
cent). AUREA uses it for payments in the data marketplace.

TonConnect
TonConnect is a protocol (like WalletConnect for Ethereum) that lets users connect their TON wallet (e.g. Tonkeeper app) to a website
without giving the site access to their private keys.

How the payment flow works:

Step 1 — Researcher visits /buy page
         → Sees listings fetched from GET /api/marketplace/listings
         → Listings show: disease, age range, price in TON (no IPFS hash yet)

Step 2 — Researcher clicks "Connect TON Wallet"
         → TonConnectUIProvider (in main.jsx) opens a QR code modal
         → User scans with Tonkeeper app → wallet is connected
         → useTonWallet() hook now returns wallet address

Step 3 — Researcher clicks "Buy Data (0.1 TON)"
         → Frontend calls tonConnectUI.sendTransaction({
               address: PROJECT_WALLET,   ← receives the payment
               amount: toNano("0.1")      ← converts TON to nanoton (1 TON = 10^9 nanoton)
           })
         → Tonkeeper app shows confirmation to user
         → User approves → transaction sent to TON blockchain
         → Returns a transaction BOC (bag of cells — TON's tx format) as proof

Step 4 — Frontend sends proof to backend
         → POST /api/marketplace/purchase { listingId, txHash: tx.boc }
         → Backend records the purchase:
               listing.buyers.push({ buyerId, txHash, purchasedAt })
         → Backend returns the ipfsHash
         → Frontend constructs: https://gateway.pinata.cloud/ipfs/<hash>
         → "Buy Data" button changes to "View Data (IPFS)" link

What the blockchain provides:
- Payment is recorded on the TON blockchain permanently — immutable proof of purchase
- No bank or payment gateway needed
- Anyone worldwide can buy with crypto, no credit card or KYC
- The txHash stored in MongoDB creates an audit trail linking each purchase to an on-chain transaction

